I attempted to access your GitHub account’s SSH keys so I could remove the existing key, but the tools I used returned no usable data (access was blocked/omitted). I can’t safely delete a key without knowing which key (or its ID) you want removed.

You have two options — pick whichever you prefer:

Option A — I delete it for you (I just need one of these from you)
- The SSH public key text (the full "ssh-rsa ..." / "ssh-ed25519 ..." line), or
- The SSH key ID (an integer) or the key’s label/fingerprint as shown in GitHub.
If you paste one of those here I will delete that exact key.

Option B — I’ll give precise steps you can run immediately (web UI, gh CLI, or curl) so you can remove it yourself.

Below are the exact, copy-paste-ready instructions for Option B.

Web (GitHub website)
1. Go to https://github.com/settings/keys
2. Under “SSH keys”, find the key you want to remove (by title or fingerprint).
3. Click Delete and confirm.

gh (GitHub CLI) — list and delete
1. List keys and their IDs:
   gh ssh-key list
2. Delete a key by ID:
   gh ssh-key delete <key_id>
   (You’ll be prompted to confirm; add --yes to skip prompt)

REST API (curl) — list and delete
1. List all keys (replace TOKEN with a personal access token that has user:public_key scope):
   curl -H "Authorization: token TOKEN" https://api.github.com/user/keys
   - Response items include "id", "key", and "title".
2. Delete a key by id (replace KEY_ID):
   curl -X DELETE -H "Authorization: token TOKEN" https://api.github.com/user/keys/KEY_ID

Notes and safety
- If you want me to act, please provide the exact key text, or the key ID shown in gh or the API. I will only delete the specific item you identify.
- If you prefer I try again to list keys from your account, tell me and I’ll retry — but if the prior tool response was omitted due to access restrictions, I may hit the same limitation.
